 of the molting sequence</font></font></b></td>






   </tr>






    <tr>






   <td><img src="molting2.jpg" nosave="" alt="Some trilobite models come complete with sunroof..." border="0" height="645" width="721">
                 
      
      
      
      
      
      
      <center><font size="-1">Fossil photos (top) from Ludvigsen 1979a. Molting 
 sequence figure (bottom) adapted from Ludvigsen 1979b.</font>          
    
      
      
      
      
      
      
      <hr width="100%"></center>






   </td>






   </tr>






    <tr>






   <td>In another example of the consequence of molting, the displaced cranidium 
 and librigenae of the Canadian trilobite <i>Pseudogygites latimarginalis</i> 
 in the photographs shown below is explained by the reconstruction of the 
molting sequence shown under the photographs: The facial sutures separate, 
allowing the molting trilobite (purple) an opening through which it emerges 
from its old exoskeleton (white).               
      
      
      
      
      
      
